===Media coverage===
The [[South African Football Association]] owns the rights to national team matches played in South Africa. SAFA currently has a contract with the [[South African Broadcasting Corporation]], to broadcast these matches. It is up to the SABC to procure the rights to matches played outside of the country.

The SABC usually shows most national team games, though they have often had problems with broadcasting weekday matches. They have previously used delayed live footage,<ref>{{cite web|title=Safa blamed for Bafana's delayed live broadcast last night|url=http://www.sabcnews.com/portal/site/SABCNews/menuitem.5c4f8fe7ee929f602ea12ea1674daeb9/?vgnextoid=aa0424b9e9928210VgnVCM10000077d4ea9bRCRD&vgnextfmt=default|publisher=SABC News|date=23 April 2010|access-date=6 March 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110427072357/http://www.sabcnews.com/portal/site/SABCNews/menuitem.5c4f8fe7ee929f602ea12ea1674daeb9/?vgnextoid=aa0424b9e9928210VgnVCM10000077d4ea9bRCRD&vgnextfmt=default|archive-date=27 April 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> and sometimes not shown matches.<ref>{{cite web|title=Another own goal for SABC|url=http://www.sport24.co.za/Soccer/BafanaBafana/Another-own-goal-for-SABC-20101010|publisher=News24|date=10 October 2010|access-date=6 March 2011|archive-date=13 May 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110513083722/http://www.sport24.co.za/Soccer/BafanaBafana/Another-own-goal-for-SABC-20101010|url-status=live}}</ref>

Most large tournaments in which the team play, such as the [[FIFA World Cup]] and [[Africa Cup of Nations]], have separate broadcast rights. [[SuperSport (South African broadcaster)|SuperSport]] purchase the pay TV rights to these tournaments, thus during these tournaments, they also show South African matches. The SABC usually holds the free to air rights to these tournaments, with the notable exception being the [[2002 FIFA World Cup]]. Those matches were shown by [[e.tv]].<ref>{{cite web
 |title=SA FREE CHANNEL WINS 2002 WORLD CUP RIGHTS
 |url=http://www.sportbusiness.com/news/134508/sa-free-channel-wins-2002-world-cup-rights
 |publisher=sportbusiness
 |date=28 September 2001 |access-date=11 May 2011 |url-status=dead
 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120310061109/http://www.sportbusiness.com/news/134508/sa-free-channel-wins-2002-world-cup-rights
 |archive-date=10 March 2012
}}</ref>

=== Controversy in 2026 FIFA World Cup Qualifiers ===
On 21 March 2025, South Africa played [[Lesotho national football team|Lesotho]] in a [[FIFA World Cup qualifiers|2026 CAF FIFA World Cup qualifier]] match. It was in this match that the coaching staff made the mistake of fielding an ineligible player, in [[Teboho Mokoena (soccer, born 1997)|Teboho Mokoena]]. The team were docked 3 points (the equivalent of points that were received after their win against Lesotho) and SAFA was fined over R216 000, while Mokoena was issued with a warning. SAFA did not appeal the decision.

